      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Method",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Make and cool the filling",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Heat ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "{{olive-oil}} of olive oil",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": " in a large frying pan over medium-high heat. Add the onion and cook for 5 minutes. Add garlic, mushroom stalks, and thyme and cook for 3 minutes. Add the ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "{{spinach}} of spinach",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": " and cook until completely wilted. Transfer to a sieve and press out all liquid. Return to the pan and cook, stirring, until the pan is dry. Season with ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "{{sea-salt-flakes}}",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": " and ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "{{black-pepper}}",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": ". Transfer to a bowl. Fold in the ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "{{chestnut-cooked}} of chestnuts",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": ", ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "{{walnuts}} of toasted walnuts",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": " and ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "{{cream-cheese}} of cream cheese",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": ". Taste and adjust seasoning. Cool completely, then refrigerate until cold.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Wrap and chill",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Heat the oven to 200°C (180°C fan). On a lightly floured surface, roll out the ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "{{puff-pastry}} of puff pastry",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": " to a rectangle large enough to enclose the filling. Sear the whole portobello mushrooms in a hot, dry pan for 2 minutes per side. Brush the pastry with ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "{{dijon-mustard}} of Dijon mustard",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": ". Arrange the portobello mushrooms in a row down the centre. Spoon the cold filling over the mushrooms and shape into a firm log. Fold the pastry over the top, press the edges firmly to seal, and crimp. Place seam-side down on a lined baking tray. Score the top and brush with beaten egg. Refrigerate for 30 minutes.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Bake",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Brush with a second coat of beaten egg. Bake for 35-40 minutes until the pastry is deep golden all over. Rest for 10 minutes before slicing with a serrated knife.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "troubleshooter",
        "attrs": {
          "rows": [
            {
              "fix": "The filling must be pressed completely dry and refrigerated cold before wrapping. Bake on a preheated tray to give the base a head start.",
              "cause": "Filling was too wet, or wellington not rested before cutting",
              "symptom": "Pastry base is soggy"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Press the seam firmly using the heel of your hand, not a crimp. Ensure the pastry is not stretched when folded.",
              "cause": "Seam was stretched rather than pressed",
              "symptom": "Pastry splits along the seam during baking"
            },
            {
              "fix": "30 minutes of chilling is the minimum. The cream cheese should firm as it cools; if the filling feels too loose, fold in an extra 50g of breadcrumbs.",
              "cause": "Not chilled long enough before baking, or filling was too soft",
              "symptom": "Filling falls out when sliced"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Puff pastry needs 200°C and two coats of egg wash. Allow the first coat to dry for 5 minutes before the second.",
              "cause": "Oven not hot enough, or egg wash not applied",
              "symptom": "Pastry is pale and underbaked"
            }
          ]
        },
        "content": []
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Where this dish lives",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "The vegetarian wellington emerged from the same impulse that produced the nut roast: a centrepiece dish for vegetarians at British Christmas and Sunday tables that could hold its own against the traditional roast. In its best versions it does rather more than that, producing a dish with a depth of flavour from the mushrooms and chestnuts that the nut roast rarely achieves. Serve with roast potatoes, gravy, and green vegetables.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
  "glossaryTerms": [],
